dsmr-localfirst (1.0-5) trixie; urgency=high

  * localfirst-rcptcheck: fail open when a system user's home cannot be searched.
    The validator runs as the unprivileged smtpd user (vpopmail), which cannot
    traverse a mode-700 private home — the useradd default — so it could not read
    the user's .qmail files and wrongly rejected every extension address (e.g.
    user-tag@domain) for such users at SMTP time. It now accepts when it cannot
    read the home, deferring the deliver-or-bounce decision to qmail-local, which
    runs as the user. Bare users and world-searchable homes are unaffected.

 -- Brian O'Reilly <fade@deepsky.com>  Thu, 04 Jun 2026 19:30:00 +0000

dsmr-localfirst (1.0-4) trixie; urgency=medium

  * localfirst-rcptcheck: validate qmail extension addressing faithfully.
    The recipient gate now resolves recipients exactly as qmail delivers them —
    the longest dash-prefix that is a real /home user is the controlling
    account, and an extension is accepted only when a matching .qmail-<ext> or
    .qmail-...default catch-all exists (a bare user always delivers). Previously
    only an exact account name matched, so legitimate tagged addresses such as
    user-twitch@domain and ~alias/.qmail aliases were rejected at SMTP time even
    though qmail would have delivered them.
  * localfirst-rcptcheck: recognise qmail locals (system) domains. A recipient
    on a control/locals domain is validated against the system layer alone, with
    no vpopmail fallthrough, so a pure system domain that carries no vpopmail
    users no longer rejects every recipient. Hybrid (localfirstdomains) and pure
    vpopmail domains are unchanged.
  * The shared system-identity predicate carries both improvements, so the
    delivery-time dispatcher routes system extensions consistently with the
    SMTP-time gate.

 -- Brian O'Reilly <fade@deepsky.com>  Thu, 04 Jun 2026 17:30:00 +0000

